Part I - Prosper Loan Exploration¶

by Kayode Fredrick ATOYEBI¶

Introduction¶

This Loan Data from Prosper (a peer-to-peer lending platform) contains 113,937 loan entries with 81 variables covering a range of loan terms, borrower demographics, and credit profiles.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset has 113,937 loan records/entries with 81 features/variables

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in the LoanStatus, LoanOriginalAmount, and EstimatedReturn features with their correlation or interaction with other variables

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Variable Description Why?
ListingCategory The category of the listing that the borrower selected when posting their listing: 0 - Not Available, 1 - Debt Consolidation, 2 - Home Improvement, 3 - Business, 4 - Personal Loan, 5 - Student Use, 6 - Auto, 7- Other, 8 - Baby&Adoption, 9 - Boat, 10 - Cosmetic Procedure, 11 - Engagement Ring, 12 - Green Loans, 13 - Household Expenses, 14 - Large Purchases, 15 - Medical/Dental, 16 - Motorcycle, 17 - RV, 18 - Taxes, 19 - Vacation, 20 - Wedding Loans To check the most profitable/popular loan category(ies)
ListingKey Unique key for each listing, same value as the 'key' used in the listing object in the API. Unique Identifier
Term The length of the loan expressed in months. To check correlation with LoanStatus
LoanStatus The current status of the loan: Cancelled, Chargedoff, Completed, Current, Defaulted, FinalPaymentInProgress, PastDue. The PastDue status will be accompanied by a delinquency bucket. The main variable in the analysis
EstimatedReturn The estimated return assigned to the listing at the time it was created. Estimated return is the difference between the Estimated Effective Yield and the Estimated Loss Rate. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009. To know the (un)profitability of some other variables
ProsperRating (Alpha) The Prosper Rating assigned at the time the listing was created between AA - HR. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009. To know how different ratings affect LoanStatus
BorrowerState The two letter abbreviation of the state of the address of the borrower at the time the Listing was created. To check correlation with LoanStatus, EstimatedReturn and ListingCategory
Occupation The Occupation selected by the Borrower at the time they created the listing. To check correlation with LoanStatus, EstimatedReturn and ListingCategory
EmploymentStatus The employment status of the borrower at the time they posted the listing. To check correlation with LoanStatus
EmploymentStatusDuration The length in months of the employment status at the time the listing was created. To check correlation with LoanStatus
IsBorrowerHomeowner A Borrower will be classified as a homowner if they have a mortgage on their credit profile or provide documentation confirming they are a homeowner. To check correlation with LoanStatus
OpenCreditLines Number of open credit lines at the time the credit profile was pulled. To check correlation with LoanStatus
OpenRevolvingAccounts Number of open revolving accounts at the time the credit profile was pulled. To check correlation with LoanStatus
InquiriesLast6Months Number of inquiries in the past six months at the time the credit profile was pulled. To know whether the individual has applied to other Fin. firms and its correlation with LoanStatus
CurrentDelinquencies Number of accounts delinquent at the time the credit profile was pulled. To check correlation with LoanStatus
IncomeRange The income range of the borrower at the time the listing was created. To check correlation with LoanStatus and EstimatedReturn
IncomeVerifiable The borrower indicated they have the required documentation to support their income. To ensure that only records with verified IncomeRange are included in the analysis
LoanOriginalAmount The origination amount of the loan. To know if some other variables influence how much is approved
LoanOriginationDate The date the loan was originated. Time Series Analysis
ListingCreationDate The date the listing was created. To filter off records before July 2009
DebtToIncomeRatio The debt to income ratio of the borrower at the time the credit profile was pulled. This value is Null if the debt to income ratio is not available. This value is capped at 10.01 (any debt to income ratio larger than 1000% will be returned as 1001%). To check correlation with LoanStatus and Prosper Rating

#select the features of interest
select_features =['ListingKey', 'LoanOriginationDate', 'LoanStatus',  
                  'Term', "ListingCreationDate", 'IncomeRange', 'IncomeVerifiable',
                  'EstimatedReturn', 'ListingCategory (numeric)',  'ProsperRating (Alpha)', 
                  'BorrowerState', 'Occupation', 'EmploymentStatus', 'EmploymentStatusDuration', 
                  'IsBorrowerHomeowner', 'OpenCreditLines', 'OpenRevolvingAccounts', 'InquiriesLast6Months', 
                  'CurrentDelinquencies',  'LoanOriginalAmount', 'DebtToIncomeRatio']
prosper_new=prosper[select_features]

#filter out entries earlier than July 2009 when most of the features takes effect to avoid null values on important variables
prosper_new=prosper_new.loc[pd.to_datetime(prosper_new.ListingCreationDate) >= '2009-07']

#rename columns
prosper_new.rename(columns={'ProsperRating (Alpha)': 'ProsperRating', "ListingCategory (numeric)": "ListingCategory"}, inplace=True)


#filter off entries where the income is not verifiable
prosper_new= prosper_new[prosper_new.IncomeVerifiable ==True]

#drop superfluous columns
prosper_new.drop(["ListingCreationDate",'IncomeVerifiable'], axis=1, inplace=True)

Reorder the variable as follows:¶

  1. Change 'Defaulted', 'Chargedoff' and all 'Past Due' buckets to 'Not Completed' as they have a higher chance of not completing
  2. Merge 'FinalPaymentInProgress with 'Completed' as they are about to make the final payment to complete the loan
  3. Leave'Current' Status as it is as they have equal chance of defaulting or completing all loan payment

#Group by income range
income_plot =prosper_new.groupby('IncomeRange')['ListingKey'].size()

#Create a function for plotting
def plotter(frame, color_code):
    #Get the total entries
    total=frame.size
    
    #plot
    if frame.index.size < 7:
        ax =frame.plot(kind='bar',figsize= (11,8),color =color_code)
        for i, v in enumerate(frame.transform(lambda x: (x/x.sum())*100)):
            ax.text(i, (v*total*0.01)+1000, f'{str(round(v,2))}%', ha='center', fontweight='bold')
    else:
        ax =frame.plot(kind='barh',figsize= (11,8),color =color_code)
        for i, v in enumerate(frame.transform(lambda x: (x/x.sum())*100)):
            ax.text((v*total*0.01)+1000, i, f'{str(round(v,2))}%', ha='center', fontweight='bold')
    
    return ax
    
plotter(income_plot, '#58508d')
plt.xlabel('Income Range')
plt.ylabel('Number of Loan Clients')
plt.suptitle('Distribution of Loan Clients Per Income Range')
plt.tight_layout(pad=3);

Observation: Seems people in the $50,000-74,999 income bracket takes out the most loans¶

#Combine some subcategories:  MS Excel was used to visually inspect the columns
prosper_new.Occupation= (prosper_new.Occupation
                             .str.strip()
                             .str.replace(r'(Sales)\s+-\s+\w+', 'Salesperson')
                             .str.replace(r'(Engineer)\s+-\s+\w+', 'Engineer')
                             .str.replace(r'(Teacher)(\'s)?(\s+)?(\w+)?', 'Teacher') #including Teacher's Aide
                             .str.replace(r'(Pilot)\s+-\s+\w+/\w+', 'Pilot')
                             .str.replace(r'(Tradesman)\s+-\s+\w+', 'Tradesman')
                             #Create a 'Health Worker' occupation
                             .str.replace(r'(Nurse)(\'s)?(\s+)?\(?\w+\)?', 'Health Worker') #including Nurse's Aide
                             .str.replace('Medical Technician', 'Health Worker')
                             .str.replace('Pharmacist', 'Health Worker')
                             .str.replace('Doctor', 'Health Worker')
                             .str.replace('Dentist', 'Health Worker')
                             .str.replace(r'(Student)\s+-\s+\w+(\s+\w+)?(\s+\w+)?', 'Student')
                         
                             .str.replace('Others','Other')
                        )

Conclusions¶

The different questions, analysis and observations provides valuable insights into loan performance, borrower characteristics, and loan features which can inform future lending decisions. For example, Computer programmers are likely to bring in more money and also completely pay off their loans. Priority could also be given to health workers who needs loan for baby&adoption needs; they are likely to pay back with handsome returns. Also, home ownership and previous record of loan deliquencies does not really indicate whether a loan would be defaulted or completely paid off. Finally, more loans were disbursed from October through January and Credit Score, Loan Term, and Loan Category determines how much a client can access
